Capstone Project

About the company

About the company In 2016, Cyclistic launched a successful bike-share offering. Since then, the program has grown to a fleet of 5,824 bicycles that are geotracked and locked into a network of 692 stations across Chicago. The bikes can be unlocked from one station and returned to any other station in the system anytime. Until now, Cyclistic’s marketing strategy relied on building general awareness and appealing to broad consumer segments. One approach that helped make these things possible was the flexibility of its pricing plans: single-ride passes, full-day passes, and annual memberships. Customers who purchase single-ride or full-day passes are referred to as casual riders. Customers who purchase annual memberships are Cyclistic members. Cyclistic’s finance analysts have concluded that annual members are much more profitable than casual riders. Although the pricing flexibility helps Cyclistic attract more customers, Moreno believes that maximizing the number of annual members will be key to future growth. Rather than creating a marketing campaign that targets all-new customers, Moreno believes there is a very good chance to convert casual riders into members. She notes that casual riders are already aware of the Cyclistic program and have chosen Cyclistic for their mobility needs. Moreno has set a clear goal: Design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members. In order to do that, however, the marketing analyst team needs to better understand how annual members and casual riders differ, why casual riders would buy a membership, and how digital media could affect their marketing tactics. Moreno and her team are interested in analyzing the Cyclistic historical bike trip data to identify trends

Scenario

“As junior data analyst working in the marketing analyst team at Cyclistic, a bike-share company in Chicago. The director of marketing believes the company’s future success depends on maximizing the number of annual memberships. Therefore, your team wants to understand how casual riders and annual members use Cyclistic bikes differently. From these insights, your team will design a new marketing strategy to convert casual riders into annual members. But first, Cyclistic executives must approve your recommendations, so they must be backed up with compelling data insights and professional data visualizations.” Riders who pay for an annual membership are more profitable than casual riders, according to data research. The marketing department is considering developing a campaign to entice casual passengers to become members. The team wants to look at the Cyclistic historical bike trip data to see whether there are any patterns in how casual and member users use bikes.

Ask

Business Objective

Three questions will guide the future marketing program: 1. How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently? 2. Why would casual riders buy Cyclistic annual memberships? 3. How can Cyclistic use digital media to influence casual riders to become members

Business Task

I will produce a report with the following deliverables: 1. A clear statement of the business task 2. A description of all data sources used 3. Documentation of any cleaning or manipulation of data 4. A summary of your analysis 5. Supporting visualizations and key findings 6. Your top three recommendations based on your analysis

Stakeholders Involved

The stakeholders involved in this project are: Director of Marketing at Cyclistic : Lily Moreno, responsible for the marketing campaigns at Cyclistic.

The Cyclistic executive team. This group makes the ultimate decision on the marketing strategy that has been recommended. They are known for their meticulous attention to detail.

Prepare

Location of Data

The data used in this project can be found here: https://divvy-tripdata.s3.amazonaws.com/index.html This data has been collected by Motivate company employed by the city of Chicago to collect data about the usage of their bikes.

Data Organisation

The data is stored in csv files that are updated on a monthly basis. For this research, the most current twelve months of data (January 2021 – December 2021) were used. The files have 13 columns that contain information such as ride id, ridership type, trip time, start and end locations, and geographic coordinates, among other things.

Credibility of the Data

Motivate, Inc., the corporation that manages the City of Chicago’s Cyclistic Bike Share programme, collects the data directly. The data is extensive and includes information from all of the rides recorded on the system, rather than just a sample. The information is current. It is published on a monthly basis and was current as of December 2021. The data is made accessible to the public by the City of Chicago.

Licensing, Privacy, Security and Accesibility

All identifying information has been removed from this data, making it anonymous. This protects privacy, but also restricts the scope of the investigation. There is insufficient data to tell whether casual riders are repeat riders or if casual riders are Chicago residents. This licence https://ride.divvybikes.com/data-license-agreement governs the distribution of this data.

Data’s ability to provide answers to this Business Question

This data is necessary in order to identify differences in how members or casual riders use the bike share programme identify trends and difference between them.

Problems with the dataset

There are some discrepancies in the structure of the data frame. The majority of the errors (duplicate records, missing fields, etc.) can be solved by data cleansing, but there are a few that require more explanation.

More information would be need in order to create a proper recommendation for a marketing campaign, such identification for each rider to know how many times a rider follow the same route or age, sex and education to find demographic observation.

Process and Clean

What tools I choosed and Why

I used Spreadsheets and power query for cleaning and explore data on first time, being easier to explore and visualize here raw data. After this export the data already cleaned on RStudio Desktop to analyse, perform calculations and visualizations.

Tableau dashboard - > Dashboard Google Slides presentation for Stakeholders -> Presentation

Integrity of Dataset

Data was examined to gain a general understanding of field content, Checking column names throughout the 12 original files and looking for missing values, trailing white spaces, duplicate records, and other data abnormalities were all part of the data assessment.

This review identified the following abnormalities:

Missing values in the start and end stations variables. Missing values in the end_lat, end_lgt, start_lat and start_lgt. Missing values in stations names. Duplicate records in ride_ID variable. Too long or too short values in the ride duration variable. After the initial review all twelve files where combined in one dataframe with 5,595,063 rows and 13 columns, character data type that would be transformed later on as we prepare data further.

All rows with empty fields or duplicate where deleted in order to don’t affect the results of the analysis getting a total of 4627058 rows already cleaned that means a 17.3%.

Split DDBB in to DataFrames

Due to the size of the data set and hardware limitations I diceded to split the data set in two data frames, one with times and dates information and another one with stations information.

Data frame with dates, type of bike and type of member.

trip_dates <- select(cy_trips, rideable_type, started_at, ended_at, member_casual)

Data frame with station names, coordinates and type of members.

trip_stations <- select(cy_trips, start_station_name, end_station_name, start_lat, start_lng, end_lat, end_lng, member_casual)

head(trip_stations)

Here I decided to create another row call “Route” to contain the route follow by the cyclist joining the name of the starting station with the ending station.

trip_stations$route <- paste(trip_stations$start_station_name, trip_stations$end_station_name, sep=" TO ")

head(trip_stations)

Created another row to contain the number of times the route was follow and omit empty ones.

routes <- trip_stations %>% 
  group_by(route, member_casual, start_lat, start_lng, end_lat, end_lng) %>% 
  count(route, name = "count", sort = TRUE)%>% 
  summarize(route,count) %>% 
  arrange(-count)

routes <- na.omit(routes)

head(routes)

Data with dates.

Add columns that list the date, month, day, and year of each ride.

trip_dates$started_at <- dmy_hm(trip_dates$started_at)
trip_dates$ended_at <- dmy_hm(trip_dates$ended_at)
trip_dates$month <- month(trip_dates$started_at, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE)
trip_dates$day <- day(trip_dates$started_at)
trip_dates$day_of_week <- wday(trip_dates$started_at, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE)
trip_dates$time <- format(trip_dates$started_at, format = "%H")

  dplyr::count(member_casual)%>%

pl <- ggplot (data = mpgCount, aes(x = "", y = n, fill = member_casual,)) 
pl <- pl + geom_col(width = 1, color = "white") + labs(x = "Total Of Riders", y = "Rider Type")
pl <- pl + geom_text(aes(x = "", y = n

summary(trip_dates$ride_length)

trip_dates %>% 
  group_by(member_casual) %>% 
  summarise(avg_ride_lenth = mean(ride_length)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = "", y = avg_ride_lenth, fill = member_casual)) +
  geom_col(color = "white") + labs(title="Trip Length Average By Member Type", x = "Avg", y = "Member Type") + 
  coord_polar("y", start=0) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#4285F4", "#F4B400")) + 
  theme_classic() +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste0(trunc(avg_ride_lenth, 0), " min")), position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), color = "white", fontface = "bold", size=8)

The duration of trips for casual users is almost double that of member users, this may be because these casual members, a large percentage are tourists who rent the bike for the whole day while the members use them for trips such as going to work or to specific places.

Rides per month

trip_dates %>% 
  group_by(member_casual, month) %>% 
  summarise(number_of_rides = n()) %>%
  arrange(member_casual, month)%>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = month, y = number_of_rides, fill = member_casual)) +

  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1)) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#4285F4", "#F4B400"))

June to September seems to be the busiest season for casual riders which coincides with the summer and vacation season reinforcing the theory that casual users may be tourists although members have a similar trend with June to October being the busiest.

Member users have a fairly balanced use throughout the week while casual users use the bikes more often on weekends.

Rides per Hour

  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust = 1)) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#4285F4", "#F4B400"))

Members have two times of the day when they use bicycles the most, between 6 a.m. and 7 a.m. and 4 p.m. and 6 p.m., which coincide with the most popular times to start work and end the workday. For casual users the most popular times are between 3 and 6 pm.

Act

Conclusion

In order to give a more accurate recommendation for a marketing campaign, further analysis and more data are needed to provide demographic specifications for the campaign and identify how many users are members or casuals and how often they use the bikes.

A trip duration membership or weekend membership would be a good idea to promote the use of bikes by tourists or casual riders. Focus the campaign on the districts 60611 and 60601 could help to push the effectiveness of the campaign, and do it in the summer months between 12 pm and 4 pm.
